You can tell it’s a tree by the way it is. We caught up with Forester Brian Williams as he was working on a replanting a harvest in Tahuya State Forest. During these replantings, the average worker will plant between 1,100 to 1,500 seedlings PER DAY (PER DAY!?). And when it comes to reforestation, we take it a bit more seriously than “that’s a tree.” Our foresters take deliberate steps to plant different species that will mimic the stand that we just harvested. In the following 10-15 years, our foresters will focus on controlling brush and noxious weeds (like scotch broom) in this area so these lil guys have the best chance possible to survive. In fact, every step of our harvest strategy is taken with sustainable forestry management in mind. Following the guidance of world-renowned forest ecologist Jerry Franklin and our Habitat Conservation Plan, we can minimize environmental impacts while still fulfilling our mission of generating revenue for our trust beneficiaries (K-12 schools, universities, and county services - like roads, libraries, fire districts and hospitals). #Washington #reforestation #forestry #replanting #Pnw

Discovering the gentle giants of Florida’s waterways: baby manatees! 🌊💙 Did you know these precious creatures, also known as ‘sea cows,’ are born weighing around 60-70 pounds and measuring about 3-4 feet in length? Despite their hefty size at birth, they rely on their mother’s milk for up to 2 years before transitioning to a plant-based diet. These curious and playful babies spend their days exploring the warm coastal waters, seeking shelter in shallow areas and enjoying the company of their protective mothers. Let’s cherish and protect these adorable ambassadors of the sea! DISCLAIMER: Manatees are federally protected animals. Any form of harassment or disturbance to these gentle creatures is strictly prohibited by law. Please DO NOT PET! Let’s ensure their safety and well-being by admiring them from a respectful distance. 🛶: @Ecoventure Tours #manatee #florida #wildlife #conservation

Sea lions are learning how to play video games! You might not see them online while you’re playing just yet, but they are having fun with their maze games. The Navy sea lions have access to the games through the US Navy Marine Mammal Program as part of their enrichment. The sea lions are trained to attach recovery lines to Navy equipment at the ocean floor that is too difficult for humans to get to. They’re free to leave the program if they’d like to, but most choose to stay. The video games might be one reason why! 📸 US Navy #sealion #navy #navyseal #gaming #videogames #goodnews
